In this second part, I will demonstrate a different automation tool I developed to manage complex Bill of Materials (BOM) data. For this project, I worked with standard data formats and converted them into a structured JSON format to streamline the engineering selection process.

The core of this application is its ability to take raw engineering data and transform it into a highly organized JSON structure. As you can see on the screen, the user can select specific standards or components from a predefined list. This ensures that the data remains consistent and follows the required engineering standards.

Once the selection is made, the program processes these JSON objects and allows the user to export them into a clean, formatted Excel file. This bridge between JSON and Excel is crucial because it takes complex, nested data and makes it readable for other departments or for final documentation.

A key feature here is the validation logic. The program doesn't just convert data; it ensures that the inputs match the specific criteria of the selected standard. If a value is out of range or incorrectly formatted, the system identifies it before the final report is generated.

This tool significantly reduces the time spent on manual data entry and formatting. By using a JSON-based backbone, we ensure that the data is not only easy to manipulate programmatically but also ready for integration with other software or databases in the future.